    <div class="container">
        <div class="header">
            <h1>🔮 How It Works</h1>
            <p>Understanding the SRE Horoscope Generator</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="section">
            <h2>🌟 What Is This?</h2>
            <p>
                The SRE Horoscope Generator combines astronomical data 
                with site reliability concepts. It generates "cosmic predictions" for your upcoming deploy or on-call rotation.
            </p>
            
            <div class="warning">
                <span style="font-size: 1.2rem;">⚠️</span>
                <div>
                    <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This tool is for entertainment purposes only. 
                    You probably shouldn't make deployment or incident response decisions based on planetary alignments.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>🎯 How Accurate Is This?</h2>
            <p>
                The SRE Horoscope Generator is as accurate at predicting incidents as all other industry standard techniques.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>🛠️ How It Works</h2>
            
            <div class="flow-step">
                <h4>1. 🌌 Astronomical Data Collection</h4>
                <p>
                    We fetch real planetary position data from NASA's JPL Horizons system, which provides precise 
                    coordinates (Right Ascension, Declination, and Distance) for celestial bodies on any given date.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="flow-step">
                <h4>2. 🎨 Stained Glass Orrery Visualization</h4>
                <p>
                    The planetary positions are rendered in a stained glass-style orrery (a model of the solar system) 
                    using HTML5 Canvas. Each planet is positioned based on its actual astronomical coordinates.
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="flow-step">
                <h4>4. 📊 Risk Assessment</h4>
                <p>
                    Based on the planetary influences, we assign an overall "cosmic risk level" for your operations, 
                    from favorable conditions to high alert periods requiring extra vigilance.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="section">
            <h2>🏗️ Technical Architecture</h2>
            
            <div class="architecture-diagram">
                <pre>
┌─────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────┐
│   NASA JPL      │───▶│   PostgreSQL     │───▶│   Node.js API   │
│   Horizons API  │    │   Database       │    │   Server        │
└─────────────────┘    └──────────────────┘    └─────────────────┘
                                                          │
                                                          ▼
┌─────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────┐    ┌─────────────────┐
│   Stained Glass │◀───│   Frontend       │◀───│   EJS Templates │
│   Orrery Canvas │    │   Dashboard      │    │   & Styling     │
└─────────────────┘    └──────────────────┘    └─────────────────┘
                </pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="section">
            <h2>🌍 Data Sources</h2>
            <p>
                We use <span class="highlight">NASA's JPL Horizons system</span>, which is the gold standard for 
                astronomical ephemeris data. This system provides:
            </p>
            <p>
                Learn more about the API in the <a href="https://ssd-api.jpl.nasa.gov/doc/horizons.html" target="_blank" style="color: #ffd700; text-decoration: underline;">official documentation</a>.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>High Precision:</strong> Accurate to fractions of an arcsecond</li>
                <li><strong>Historical Data:</strong> Planetary positions dating back centuries</li>
                <li><strong>Future Predictions:</strong> Reliable forecasts for years ahead</li>
                <li><strong>Multiple Bodies:</strong> Sun, Moon, planets, asteroids, and comets</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>
                When NASA data is unavailable, we fall back to mathematical approximations based on 
                orbital mechanics to ensure the tool remains functional.
            </p>
        </div>
        
